Problem 1

  1. Use regular expressions to determine the number of speaking lines The Complete Works of William Shakespeare.
complete_url <- "http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/100/pg100.txt"
shakespeare <- complete_url %>%
  getURL() %>%
  strsplit(split = "\r\n") %>%
  magrittr::extract2(1)
length(shakespeare)
## [1] 124787
shakespeare1 <- grep(shakespeare, pattern = "^  [A-Z]+\\.", value = FALSE)
head(shakespeare1)
## [1]  105 2870 2871 2874 2879 2880
tail(shakespeare1)
## [1] 123917 123919 123921 123928 123936 123944
123944-2870
## [1] 121074

The first speaking line according to grep is 2870. The one before that(105) is just the line ASCII., which is not a speaking line. The last speaking line is at 123944. Taking the difference between the first and last speaking line, there are 121074 speaking lines.

  1. Make a bar chart displaying the top 100 characters with the greatest number of lines.
characters <- grep("  [A-Z]+ ?[A-Z]+\\.", shakespeare) 

nameSeperate <- unlist(strsplit(shakespeare[characters], "\\. "))
namesOnly <- grep("  [A-Z]+ ?[A-Z]+", nameSeperate, value = TRUE)
namesOnly <- data.frame(namesOnly)

totalLines <- namesOnly %>%
  group_by(namesOnly) %>%
  summarize(N = n()) %>%
  arrange(desc(N))

totalLines <- subset(totalLines, N>= 76)
plot <- ggplot(data = totalLines, aes(x = reorder(namesOnly, N), y = N))
plot + geom_bar(stat = "identity") + coord_flip()
